<!-- ========== WHAT ARE PEPTIDES ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>What Exactly Are Peptides?</h2>

<p>Peptides are short chains of amino acids, typically between two and fifty units long. They're the building blocks of larger proteins like collagen, elastin, and keratin.</p>

<p>Think of amino acids as individual letters, peptides as words, and proteins as full sentences. Without the right words, you can't build the sentence your body needs.</p>

<p>Your body produces peptides naturally. They act as signaling molecules, delivering instructions to cells about what to build, what to repair, and what to protect.</p>

<p>When a peptide reaches a skin cell, it might trigger collagen synthesis, reduce inflammation, or accelerate wound healing. The problem is that as you age, your body produces fewer of these signals, and the ones it does produce become less effective.</p>

<p>That's where supplemental peptides come in. Applied topically in serums and creams, or administered systemically through injections, peptides can reintroduce those repair signals and prompt your body to do what it used to do on its own.</p>

<!-- ========== COLLAGEN PROBLEM ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The Collagen Problem: Why Your Skin Changes with Age</h2>

<p>Collagen is the most abundant protein in your body. It's the scaffolding that keeps your skin firm, your joints flexible, and your hair strong.</p>

<p>Starting in your mid-twenties, your body begins producing less of it. By the time you reach 40, that decline accelerates noticeably.</p>

<p>Research published in the <em>American Journal of Pathology</em> found that fibroblasts from young adults (ages 18&ndash;29) produced roughly 82 nanograms of type I procollagen per sample. Individuals over 80 produced just 56 nanograms (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16227487/">Varani et al., 2006</a>).</p>

<p>It's not just about making less collagen, either. The collagen you still have becomes fragmented and disorganized over time. The fibers lose their neat, parallel structure and begin to tangle and weaken.</p>

<p>Sun exposure, pollution, smoking, and poor nutrition all accelerate this process.</p>

<div class="d-a">
