<!-- ========== FAQ ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="faq">
  <details>
    <summary>Can I use peptides with retinol?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Yes. Peptides and retinoids complement each other well. Some dermatologists recommend alternating nights (peptide serum one evening, retinol the next) if your skin is sensitive. For resilient skin, both can be used in the same routine.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Why can't I combine copper peptides with vitamin C?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Copper ions can oxidize L-ascorbic acid (the most common form of vitamin C), reducing its effectiveness. Some newer vitamin C derivatives are more stable with copper, but as a general rule, apply them at different times of day or on alternating days.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>How long does it take for peptides to show results?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Most people notice improved hydration and texture within 1&ndash;2 weeks. Visible wrinkle reduction typically takes 8&ndash;12 weeks. Hair growth from scalp-applied peptides usually requires 12&ndash;16 weeks of consistent use.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Are peptide serums better than collagen supplements?</summary>
    <div class="fa">They work differently. Topical peptide serums signal your skin to produce its own collagen in situ. Oral collagen supplements provide amino acid building blocks that may support collagen production systemically. Many people use both.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Do peptides work for all skin types?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Yes. Peptides are among the most universally tolerated active ingredients in skincare. They're suitable for dry, oily, combination, and sensitive skin types. The carrier formulation (cream vs. serum) matters more than the peptide itself for skin-type compatibility.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Is GHK-Cu safe for long-term use?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Topical GHK-Cu has an excellent long-term safety profile. It's a naturally occurring peptide in human blood plasma, and concentrations decline with age. Replenishing it topically has not shown adverse effects in published studies spanning months of daily use.</div>
  </details>
  <details>
    <summary>Can peptides replace Botox for wrinkles?</summary>
    <div class="fa">Neurotransmitter-inhibiting peptides like Argireline can soften expression lines, but they don't produce the same degree of muscle relaxation as botulinum toxin injections. Peptides are better suited for prevention and mild correction rather than deep, established expression lines.</div>
  </details>
</div>

<!-- ========== BOTTOM LINE ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>The Bottom Line</h2>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Summary</div>
  <p>Peptides represent a genuine advancement in skincare science. They're not replacing retinoids or sunscreen, but they work alongside both to create a more complete anti-aging strategy. For most people, adding a well-formulated peptide serum is the single easiest upgrade they can make to their routine.</p>
</div>

<p>Start with one peptide. GHK-Cu is the strongest all-around choice for both skin and hair. Give it twelve weeks of consistent use before evaluating results.</p>

<p>If you're already using retinoids and sunscreen, a peptide serum fills the remaining gap in your routine: active collagen stimulation. If you're new to active skincare entirely, peptides are a forgiving starting point with a low risk of irritation.</p>

<p>The science behind peptides is solid and growing. They're among the most effective, lowest-risk tools available for fighting collagen loss and supporting hair health.</p>

